    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Most (all?) shells can [execute stdin](http://stackoverflow.com/a/9966150/152142). E.g.:\n\n```\necho ls | bash\n```\n\nYet in Vim, if I have a buffer with these contents:\n\n```\nls\n```\n\nand then execute any of these:\n\n```\n:%!\n:%w !\n:%r !\n```\n\nnothing happens. The buffer contents should pipe to `&shell` if `:!` has no arguments.\n\nAlso, `:!` does not work with a new, unsaved buffer. It should.\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> nothing happens. The buffer contents should pipe to &shell if :!` has no arguments.\n\nI don't see why we couldn't do that (though I'm sure someone will come up with a myriad reasons, perhaps we can ask vim_dev as well). That said, I usually edit files with the sh extension and then run then with SingleCompile.\n\n> Also, :! does not work with a new, unsaved buffer. It should.\n\nAt first sight, this indeed seems like a limitation we inherited from vanilla vim, and since we only use pipes there's no reason why we can't do this. (then again, I recall now that Vim also saves the output to a temp file, which it could do for unsaved buffers equally well).\n",
            "created_at": "2015-02-23T19:05:03Z",
